  "prompt": "How can we prove that the square root of 2 is irrational?",
  "response": "To prove that the square root of 2 is irrational, we can use a proof by contradiction. Here\u2019s how the proof works:\n\n1. **Assumption**: Assume that \\(\\sqrt{2}\\) is rational. This means that it can be expressed as a fraction in the form \\(\\frac{p}{q}\\), where \\(p\\) and \\(q\\) are integers that have no common factors other than 1 (i.e., they are coprime), and \\(q \\neq 0\\).\n\n2. **Equation Setup**: From our assumption, we can write:\n   \\[\n   \\sqrt{2} = \\frac{p}{q}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Squaring Both Sides**: Squaring both sides gives:\n   \\[\n   2 = \\frac{p^2}{q^2}\n   \\]\n\n4. **Rearranging the Equation**: By multiplying both sides by \\(q^2\\), we get:\n   \\[\n   p^2 = 2q^2\n   \\]\n   This equation implies that \\(p^2\\) is even because it is equal to \\(2q^2\\), which is clearly even (as it is two times an integer).\n\n5. **Implication for \\(p\\)**: Since \\(p^2\\) is even, it follows that \\(p\\) must also be even (the square of an odd number is odd). Therefore, we can write:\n   \\[\n   p = 2k\n   \\]\n   for some integer \\(k\\).\n\n6. **Substituting Back**: Substituting \\(p = 2k\\) back into the equation \\(p^2 = 2q^2\\) gives:\n   \\[\n   (2k)^2 = 2q^2\n   \\]\n   Simplifying this, we have:\n   \\[\n   4k^2 = 2q^2\n   \\]\n   Dividing both sides by 2 results in:\n   \\[\n   2k^2 = q^2\n   \\]\n\n7. **Implication for \\(q\\)**: This equation shows that \\(q^2\\) is also even, which implies that \\(q\\) is even.\n\n8. **Conclusion**: Since both \\(p\\) and \\(q\\) are even, they have at least 2 as a common factor. This contradicts our initial assumption that \\(p\\) and \\(q\\) have no common factors other than 1.\n\n9. **Final Statement**: Therefore, our assumption that \\(\\sqrt{2}\\) is rational must be false, and we conclude that \\(\\sqrt{2}\\) is irrational.\n\nThis completes the proof that the square root of 2 is irrational.",
